		<body>
		<pb n="1"/>
		
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Barbados</placeName> <date>21 Nov. 1847</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
		  <p rend="indent(2)">I have much pleasure in acknowledging<lb/> receipt your esteemed favor 3 ultimo&#44; and after the same<lb/> was in my possession[&#63;] five days&#44; I received the &#34;occidents&#34;<lb/> which I have delivered to your several subscribers&#44; and<lb/> only two days ago the parcel directed to the Consul<lb/> at <placeName>Grenada</placeName>.  I am sorry to say I have had a deal<lb/> of trouble ere the latter could be obtained&#44; and then had<lb/> to pay $50 freight on it&#8211;for your guidance and future<lb/> government&#44; I must inform you that the Captain of<lb/> the &#34;Kingston&#34; Committed a breach of trust by opening<lb/> the parcel to ascertain the contents&#44; this he cannot deny&#44;<lb/> as he publicly told my Father in Law <persName>M. M. I. D. Azive</persName>&#45;<lb/>&#45;do&#44; had it have been of the greatest consequence he<lb/> would have done the same&#44; therefore I consider it a duty<lb/> you owe to yourself to represent his conduct to his<lb/> employer&#44; and as you are I understand intimate with<lb/> the Several Editors of the Press&#44; that you request them<lb/> to give publicity to the same&#44; so that the public may<lb/> be guarded against such a man&#44; for he would not<lb/> hesitate in my opinion to gratify his curiosity to open<lb/> any letter that may be entrusted to his care&#44; my Father<lb/> told him&#44; that his conduct should be represented&#44;<lb/> when he made for answer &#34;if that was the case<lb/> he would never take charge of any more letter or<lb/> parcels from any of our friends&#34;&#8211;this you need not<lb/> care</p>

		<pb n="2"/>
		
			<p>about&#44; for should the &#34;Kingston&#34; at any time be put<lb/> up for this port&#44; you can always send any thing you<lb/> may have under cover <del>of</del> <persName>S. P. Musson Esq.</persName> Addressing that<lb/> Gentn. A few lines&#44; requesting him to deliver it over to me&#44;<lb/> but let it be in a different hand writing to yours&#8211;<lb/> I must now also acquaint you that some time back<lb/> I received a parcel of your &#34;occidents&#34; through the Post<lb/> Office from one of the Islands&#44; as the Catn. Of the vessel<lb/> did not dispose of his cargo here&#44; and tried another<lb/> market&#44; and took all letters and parcels with him&#44;<lb/> and for which I had to pay &#36;1.25 postage&#44; which I<lb/> shall deduct together with the &#162;50 now paid&#44; when<lb/> I remit you the annual subscription to the &#34;Occident&#34;<lb/> by the first conveyance&#44; the Books shall be forwarded<lb/> to <placeName>Grenada</placeName>&#44; and in future should you have any<lb/> thing to send under my care&#44; be particular in re&#45;<lb/>&#45;questing the Captn. to deliver them on arrival to<lb/> the health officer when he boards the vessel&#44; as you<lb/> cannot imagine the trouble I invariably have<lb/> with them&#8211;my Father has by this conveyance<lb/> addressed my sister also on the Subject&#44; and in <sic>re&#45;<lb/>&#45;ferance</sic> to her you will learn all particulars.&#8211;I<lb/> am obliged for your attention in having inserted<lb/> the proceedings of our vestry meeting&#44; and in all<lb/> consider the October number very interesting&#8211;I<lb/> am sorry to say up to the present I have not<lb/> received the missing or August numbers&#44; nor of it<lb/> the daily service you sent by the same vessel&#44;<lb/> and of which I some time back communicated</p>

		<pb n="3"/>
		
			<p>to you&#44; the Captn. strongly denying having had<lb/> them on board&#8211;please to tender my regards to<lb/> the <persName>Carvalho&#39;s</persName>&#44; and deliver the enclosed to my sister.<lb/>  with kind wishes from my wife and children&#44; as well<lb/> as myself</p>
		  <p rend="indent(3)">I remain</p>
		  <p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir</p>
		  <p rend="indent(4)">your&#39;s most truly</p>
		  <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Samuel E Daniels</persName></p>
				<p>Watson &amp; Son</p>
				<p><placeName>129 N. Front Street</placeName></p>

